Chapter 7. Introduction to time series analysis in the frequency domain

Eigenvectors and eigenvalues of covariance matrices

Univariate time series model is a vector-valued random variable \(Y_{1:N}\) which we suppose has a covariance matrix \(V\) which is an \(N \times N\) matrix with entries \(V_{mn} = \operatorname{Cov}(Y_m, Y_n)\).

\(V\) is a non-negative definite symmetric matrix, and therefore has \(N\) non-negative eigenvalues \(\lambda_1,\dots,\lambda_N\) with corresponding eigenvectors \(\ev_1,\dots,\ev_N\) such that \[ V u_n = \lambda_n u_n.\] These eigenvectors are orthogonal: \[u_{m}^{\mathrm{T}} u_{n}=0 \text { if } m \neq n\]

The components of Y in the directions of different eigenvectors are uncorrelated. If we knew V , we could convert the model to a representation where the observable random variables are uncorrelated. We could transform the data into its components in the directions of the eigenvectors of the model. An uncorrelated (or, in the Gaussian case, independent) model would then become appropriate for this transformation of the data.

N <- 100; phi <- 0.8; sigma <- 1
V <- matrix(NA,N,N)
for(m in 1:N) for(n in 1:N) V[m,n]<-sigma^2*phi^abs(m-n)/(1-phi^2) 
V_eigen <- eigen(V,symmetric=TRUE) 
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# each vector is a 100-length vector, (corresponds to x axis)
matplot(V_eigen$vectors[,1:5],type="l") 
matplot(V_eigen$vectors[,6:9],type="l")

round(V_eigen$values[1:9],2)
## [1] 24.59 23.44 21.73 19.70 17.57 15.51 13.61 11.91 10.42

We see that the eigenvalues are decreasing. In this model, the components of \(Y_{1:N}\) with highest variance correspond to long-period oscillations.

Suppose \(\{Y_n,-\infty<n<\infty\}\) has a stationary autocovariance function \(\gamma_h\). Write \(\Gamma\) for the infinite matrix with entries \(\Gamma_{m, n}=\gamma_{m-n}\) for all integers \(m\) and \(n\)

An infinite eigenvector is a sequence \(u=\{u_n, -\infty<n<\infty\}\) with corresponding eigenvalue \(\lambda\) such that \[\Gamma u = \lambda u,\] writing out the matrix multiplication explicitly, \[ \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty} \Gamma_{m, n} u_{n}=\lambda u_{m} \quad \text { for all } m \] We look for a sinusoidal solution \(u_n = e^{i\omega n}\). \[ \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty} \Gamma_{m, n} u_{n}=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty} \gamma_{m-n} u_{n} = u_m\lambda(\omega) \] where \[\lambda(\omega)=\sum_{h=-\infty}^{\infty} \gamma_{h} e^{-i \omega h}\] is the spectral density function and is calculated as the Fourier transform of \(\gamma_h\) at frequency \(\omega\).

Spectrum of a time series model

Frequency components of \(Y_{1:N}\) are the components in the directions of its eigenvectors, or Fourier basis. We write \[ \begin{aligned} &C_{n}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{k=1}^{N} Y_{k} \cos \left(\omega_{n} k\right) \text { for } 0 \leq n \leq N / 2\\ &S_{n}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{k=1}^{N} Y_{k} \sin \left(\omega_{n} k\right) \text { for } 1 \leq n \leq N / 2 \end{aligned} \]

Similarly, the frequency components of data \(y_{1:N}\) are \[ \begin{aligned} c_{n} &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{k=1}^{N} y_{k} \cos \left(\omega_{n} k\right) \text { for } 0 \leq n \leq N / 2 \\ s_{n} &=\frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{k=1}^{N} y_{k} \sin \left(\omega_{n} k\right) \text { for } 1 \leq n \leq N / 2 \end{aligned} \]

The frequency components \((C_{0:N/2}, S_{1:N/2})\) are asymptotically uncorrelated. Moving to the frequency domain (i.e., transforming the data to its frequency components) has decorrelated the data.

The power of a wave is proportional to the square of its amplitude. The spectral density gives the mean square amplitude of the components at each frequency, and therefore gives the expected power. The spectral density function can therefore be called the power spectrum.

Data analysis under the frequency domain

y <- read.table(file="data/ann_arbor_weather.csv",header=TRUE) 
head(y[,1:9],3)
##   Year Low High Hi_min Lo_max Avg_min Avg_max Mean Precip
## 1 1900  -7   50     36     12      18    34.7 26.3   1.06
## 2 1901  -7   48     37     20      17    31.8 24.4   1.45
## 3 1902  -4   41     27     11      15    30.4 22.7   0.60

We have to deal with the NA measurement for 1955. A simple approach is to replace the NA by the mean. What are the strengths and weaknesses of these approaches?

low <- y$Low  # low is the sequence of low temperature data series
low[is.na(low)] <- mean(low, na.rm=TRUE)  # set NA values to mean
spectrum(low, main="Unsmoothed periodogram")

To smooth, we use the default periodogram smoother in R.

spectrum(low, spans=c(3,5,3), main="Smoothed periodogram",ylim=c(15,100))
